EP  - 56
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/08/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(92)90049-P
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002219969290049P
AB  - The internalization theory of multinational firms proposes that direct international investment occurs when a firm has information-related intangible assets with public good properties. We find that firms with characteristics suggesting the presence of information-based assets experience a significantly positive stock price reaction upon announcing a foreign acquisition. On the other hand, firms apparently lacking such assets experience at best zero abnormal returns upon announcing overseas acquisitions.
